  "prompt": "Will people still be able to have websites with no net neutrality?",
  "response": "Yes, people will still be able to have websites even without net neutrality. The concept of net neutrality refers to the principle that internet service providers (ISPs) should treat all data on the internet equally and not discriminate or charge differently based on user, content, website, platform, application, or method of communication. Without net neutrality, ISPs could potentially prioritize certain websites or services over others, slow down access to some sites, or charge higher rates for faster access.\n\nHowever, the existence of individual websites is not directly dependent on net neutrality. Anyone can still create and host a website. The main concern without net neutrality is the potential for unequal access or performance, where larger companies might pay for better service, potentially sidelining smaller sites with less traffic or resources. This could impact the user experience and accessibility of certain websites, but it does not prevent people from creating or having them.",
